					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It's easy. <br />1. They bleed as far as LC contour doing damped oscillations. So, you can play with this to find out most authentic visualization.<br />2. Color of bleed is phase of BW luma change respect to chroma burst. As we know that BW luma change aligned to pixels and in PAL case there are 6 scanline shift cycle. So, you can calculate the bleeding HUE to any pixel position. It can be done by measuring or result observing on authentic CRT TV.<br /><br />In fact, those bleeding is artefacts and engineers trying to rid off them. I recall that correct adjustment of the decoder reduces them to a minimum making it imperceptible. In the opposite case, they can be even brighter than the color. Like that rainbow effect in Sonic or Shinobi games on MegaDrive/Genesis.<br /><img src="http://img269.imageshack.us/img269/6063/28117145.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://i1060.photobucket.com/albums/t449/sonik_br/IMG_20130101_223542_zpsaaccae99.jpg" alt="Image" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

